'''''Madame de La Carlière,''''' sub-titled ''On the inconsequence of public judgement of our actions,'' is a fable written by the French writer [[Denis Diderot]] in 1772, and published for the first time in 1798.<ref>Œuvres complètes de [[Denis Diderot|Diderot]] éditées par [[Jacques-André Naigeon|Naigeon]], Paris, Desray, 1798.</ref>

Preceded by ''[[Ceci n'est pas un conte|This is not a fable]]'' and followed by ''[[Supplément au voyage de Bougainville|Supplement to the Voyage of Bougaineville]]'', it forms a [[triptych]] of moral fables written in 1772<ref>[[Denis Diderot|Diderot]] indicated the end of his revisions in a letter to [[Friedrich Melchior, Baron von Grimm]] dated the  23 September 1772.</ref> that would appear in the Literary Correspondence in 1773.<ref>For more details on this triptych, we may read the introduction written for the article consecrated in the first volume, ''This is not a fable.''</ref>

''Madame de La Carlière'' takes its name from the mother of Sophie Volland, Élisabeth Françoise Brunel de La Carlière.<ref>Raymond Trousson, Denis Diderot, Paris, Tallandier, 2005, p. 212.</ref>

In 1988, ''Madame de La Carlière'' was performed as a stage piece alongside Diderot's novel ''Rameau's Nephew'' at [[New York University]], as part of a celebration commemorating the 200th anniversary of the [[French Revolution]] and the [[Declaration of the Rights of Man]].<ref name="nyu">Bernstein, Richard, "This Time, Bicentennial Is France's," ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 29, 1988.</ref>

==Bibliography==
