{{Infobox musical composition | name = Symphony No. 5 | subtitle = ''Washington Mosaics'' | type = | composer = {{nowrap|[[Aulis Sallinen]]}} | image = | caption = | border = Yes | movements = 5 | dedication = | key = | catalogue = [[Opus number|Op.]]&nbsp;57 | composed = {{start date|1984}}–85 (r. 1987) | duration = Approx. 38 minutes | premiere_date = {{start date|1985|10|10|df=y}} | premiere_location = [[Kennedy Center]], [[Washington, D.C.]], United States | premiere_conductor = [[Mstislav Rostropovich]] | premiere_performers = [[National Symphony Orchestra]] }}
The '''Symphony No.&nbsp;5''', '''''Washington Mosaics''''', [[Opus number|Op]].&nbsp;57, is an orchestral composition by the Finnish composer [[Aulis Sallinen]], who wrote the piece from 1984–85, revising the finale in 1987. The [[National Symphony Orchestra]], the commissioning institution, premiered the work in 10&nbsp;October 1985 at the [[Kennedy Center]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], under the direction of its music director, [[Mstislav Rostropovich]].
== Composition == === History === [[File:RIAN archive 438589 Mstislav Rostropovich.jpg|thumb| upright|[[Mstislav Rostropovich]], who commissioned Sallinen's Fifth Symphony and conducted its world premiere]]
=== Structure === The symphony is in five movements: # Washington Mosaics&nbsp;I # Intermezzo&nbsp;I # Intermezzo&nbsp;II # Intermezzo&nbsp;III (''attacca'') # Washington Mosaics&nbsp;II
=== Instrumentation === According to the publisher, [http://www.musicsalesclassical.com/composer/work/7939 Novello & Co], Symphony No.&nbsp;5 is scored for the following: *'''[[Woodwind section|Woodwind]]''': 4&nbsp;[[flute]]s (2&nbsp;doubling [[piccolo]]), 4&nbsp;[[oboe]]s, 4&nbsp;[[clarinet]]s in B{{music|flat}} (1&nbsp;doubling E{{music|flat}} clarinet, 1&nbsp;doubling B{{music|flat}} [[bass clarinet]]), 4&nbsp;[[bassoon]]s (1&nbsp;doubling [[contrabassoon]]) *'''[[Brass section|Brass]]''': 6&nbsp;[[French horn|horn]]s in F, 4&nbsp;[[trumpet]]s in B{{music|flat}}, 4&nbsp;[[trombone]]s, 1&nbsp;[[tuba]] *'''[[Percussion section|Percussion]]''': [[timpani]], 4&nbsp;percussionists ([[bass drum]], [[military drum]], [[snare drum]], [[tenor drum]], [[tom-tom]]s, [[bongo drum]]s, [[wood block]]s, [[castanets]], [[tam-tam]], [[cymbals]], [[suspended cymbal]], [[Triangle (musical instrument)|triangle]], [[Cowbell (instrument)|cowbell]], [[glockenspiel]], [[xylophone]], [[vibraphone]], [[marimba]], [[tubular bells]]) *'''[[String section|String]]s''': [[violin]]s, [[viola]]s, [[cello]]s, [[double bass]]es, [[harp]], [[celesta]], [[piano]]
== Reception == === Notable performances === [[File:Kennedy Center - panoramio.jpg|thumb|The [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts]], at which the NSO premiered Sallinen's Fifth Symphony]]
The Fifth Symphony had its world premiere on 10&nbsp;October 1985, with Mstislav Rostropovich conducting the National Symphony Orchestra (NSO) at the Kennedy Center; also on the program was [[Jean Sibelius|Sibelius's]] tone poem, ''[[En saga]]'', and [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven's]] [[Symphony No. 2 (Beethoven)|Second Symphony]].{{sfnp|Tuck|1985|p=|ps=none}} ''The Washington Post'' reviewed the work with ambivalence, calling it a "big, ambitious new symphony" with "genuinely moving moments" that nonetheless was "more intriguing than convincing," its "disjointed brilliance" unable "to resolve emotionally".{{sfnp|Tuck|1985|p=|ps=none}} Three days later, Rostropovich and the NSO played the Fifth Symphony at [[Avery Fisher Hall]] in New York,{{sfnp|Rockwell|1985|p=|ps=none}} along with [[Dmitri Shostakovich|Shostakovich's]] [[Symphony No. 5 (Shostakovich)|Fifth Symphony]] and [[Joseph Haydn|Haydn's]] [[Cello Concerto No. 1 (Haydn)|Cello Concerto in C&nbsp;major]] (Rostropovich serving as soloist).{{sfnp|McLellan|1985|p=|ps=none}} On 23&nbsp;September 1988, Rostropovich and the NSO performed the revised version of the Fifth, again at the Kennedy Center in Washington; also on the program was [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart's]] serenade for strings, ''[[Eine Kleine Nachtmusik]]'', and [[Edvard Grieg|Grieg's]] two ''[[Peer Gynt (Grieg)| Peer Gynt Suites]]''.{{sfnp|McLellan|1988|p=|ps=none}}
The British premiere took place on 15&nbsp;February 1987, with [[Okko Kamu]] conducting the [[London Philharmonic]] at the [[Royal Festival Hall]]; also on the program was [[Charles Gounod|Gounod's]] ''[[St. Cecilia Mass]]''.{{sfnp|Griffiths|1987|p=|ps=none}} The performance of Sallinen's Fifth, which commenced London's three-month multi-venue, multi-orchestra 'Spotlight on Finland' music festival, was received positively, with ''The Financial Times'' characterizing the work as consisting of "icy fragments of symphonic material [that] have been chipped off to clink and tinkle in Sallinen's structural cocktail shaker".{{sfnp|Loppert|1987|p=|ps=none}} While noting the Fifth Symphony's "allusions to other music" (in particular its "post-Sibelian desolation"), ''The Sunday Times'' applauded the "vitality of Sallinen's rhythms and the sheer eventfulness of his scoring," as well as his "imaginative and masterly ... handling of the large orchestra".{{sfnp|Cairns|1987|p=|ps=none}}
=== Recordings === To date, Symphony No.&nbsp;5 has received three recordings, the first of which is from 1987 with Okko Kamu conducting the Helsinki Philharmonic on the [[Warner Classics|Finlandia]] label. Finnish conductor [[:fi:Ari Rasilainen|Ari Rasilainen]] has also recorded the symphony as part of [[Classic Produktion Osnabrück|cpo's]] compendium of Sallinen's orchestral works. The Fifth Symphony joins the [[Symphony No. 3 (Sallinen)|Third]] (Op.&nbsp;35, 1975) on the penultimate volume of the cpo series. In his review of this CD (cpo&nbsp;999970-2), ''[[Fanfare Magazine|Fanfare's]]'' Phillip Scott applauds Rasilainen for "performances of sensitivity and clarity, aided by a stunning recording", albeit played with less obvious irony than [[James DePriest|DePriest's]] effort with the [[Malmö Symphony Orchestra]]. Calling the Fifth and the Third "the pinnacle of Sallinen's orchestral work", he concludes: "Anyone curious about the symphony in contemporary music should own this [cpo] disc".{{sfnp|Scott|2009|p=227–29|ps=none}} Writing for the ''[[American Record Guide]]'', Paul Cook describes Rasilainen's interpretation of Symphony No.&nbsp;5 (relative to his handling of the Third) "much more adroit and he gets it exactly right ... Despite my quibbles [on the Third], this is an excellent release and I think the Fifth deserves your attention".{{sfnp|Cook|2008|p= 166|ps=none}}
